\begin_layout Subsection
Reduced Lapping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lapped transforms have complex interactions with variable transform sizes.
 In a previous version of Daala that used maximum lapping width for any
 given transform size, making block size decisions based on rate-distortion
 optimization (RDO) proved computationally intractable.
 This is why the lapping as implemented in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EggePCS"

\end_inset

 was fixed at 8-point almost everywhere, with the exception that an 8x8
 block being subdivided into 4 4x4 blocks used 4-point lapping on the internal
 boundaries.
 This caused 4x4 transform blocks to have 4-point lapping on two sides and
 8-point lapping on the other two sides.
 In the current version of Daala, only 4-point lapping is used on all block
 boundaries.
 Although it makes textures slightly worse and causes slightly more blocking
 artefacts, the ringing on edges is significantly reduced by using 4-point
 lapping.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reduced Overhead Entropy Coder
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The original entropy coder in Daala is based on a multiply-free algorithm
 described in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "stuiver1998piecewise"

\end_inset

.
 This version adds an alternative to the partition function for mapping
 values from frequency counts to the coder's current range.
 The new function is about 3x as complex as the old one, but is a better
 approximation of the ideal function, while still having an order of magnitude
 less complexity than a division.
 The inverse mapping does require division by the constant three, but this
 can be turned into multiplication (or avoided entirely).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finer Chroma Quantization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:finer-chroma"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among the most visible artefacts from the Daala version in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EggePCS"

\end_inset

 are chroma quantization artefacts caused by the chroma quantization being
 coarser than luma quantization at all bitrates.
 Since then, the chroma quantizers have change to be coarser than luma at
 high bitrate, but finer at low bitrate.
 Although this results in a significant improvement in visual quality, it
 is obviously a regression in all the commonly-used luma-only metrics.
\end_layout

